<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41207728</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>12</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>12</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1558-1381</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>37</Volume><Issue>1</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Feb</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Physical medicine and rehabilitation clinics of North America</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Phys Med Rehabil Clin N Am</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Paralympic Training: Sports Performance and Training Methods.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>99</StartPage><EndPage>115</EndPage><MedlinePgn>99-115</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.pmr.2025.08.012</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S1047-9651(25)00071-3</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>To become a Paralympian and sustain that level, effective training is particularly important. Training extends further than just improving one's physical abilities through strength and conditioning. Training the mind, improving biomechanics, recovery, and using technology all aid in improving the athlete's overall performance. This article focuses on summarizing the current research regarding adaptive athletes while extrapolating from the able-bodied research when research is limited.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Latorre</LastName><ForeName>Johan</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation, University of Alabama at Birmingham, Birmingham, AL, USA. Electronic address: jlatorre@uabmc.edu.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><